JOIN
---
🧠 What is JOIN?
👉 JOIN = Combine data from multiple tables
Think like this:
One table has students
Another table has courses
JOIN helps you connect them
---
📘 Example Tables
🔹 Table 1: students
id	name
1	Rahul
2	Amit
3	Neha
---
🔹 Table 2: courses
student_id	course
1	AWS
2	Linux
4	DevOps
---
🔗 Types of JOIN (L1 + L2 Basics)
---
1  INNER JOIN (Most Used 🔥)
👉 Returns only matching data
---
🔹 Query
SELECT s.name, c.course
FROM students s
INNER JOIN courses c
ON s.id = c.student_id;
---
🔹 Output
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Amit	Linux

👉 Neha is not shown (no course)
👉 DevOps not shown (no matching student)
---
🧠 Easy Meaning
👉 “Give me only common data from both tables”
---

2 LEFT JOIN
👉 Returns:
All data from left table
Matching data from right table
---
🔹 Query
SELECT s.name, c.course
FROM students s
LEFT JOIN courses c
ON s.id = c.student_id;
---
🔹 Output
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Amit	Linux
Neha	NULL
👉 Neha appears (no course → NULL)
---
🧠 Easy Meaning
👉 “Give me everything from left + matching from right”
---

3 RIGHT JOIN
👉 Opposite of LEFT JOIN
---
🔹 Query
SELECT s.name, c.course
FROM students s
RIGHT JOIN courses c
ON s.id = c.student_id;
---
🔹 Output
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Amit	Linux
NULL	DevOps
---
🧠 Easy Meaning
👉 “Give me everything from right + matching from left”
---

4 FULL JOIN (Concept)
👉 Returns everything from both tables
---
🔹 Output Concept
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Amit	Linux
Neha	NULL
NULL	DevOps
---
⚠️ Important: JOIN Condition
ON s.id = c.student_id
👉 This is how tables are connected
👉 Without it → ❌ wrong data (cartesian product)
---
🚫 Common Mistake
❌ Missing ON:
SELECT * FROM students JOIN courses;
👉 Creates huge wrong data
---
🧠 Real-Life Examples
👉 In companies:
Users + Orders
Employees + Departments
Customers + Payments
---
🔹 Example: Employee + Department
SELECT e.name, d.department_name
FROM employees e
JOIN departments d
ON e.dept_id = d.id;
---
